This is a very moving story. I'm proud Cpl. Avant was finally able to be given the proper burial he and his family deserved.A procession to honor U.S. Army Cpl. Joe T. Avant passed through Madison this morning on its way to Greenwood for burial. In late 1950, the 20-year-old Avant was a member of Heavy Mortar Company, 31st Infantry Regiment, 7th Infantry Division, 31st Regimental Combat Team serving in Korea. He was reported missing in action Nov. 30, 1950, in the vicinity of the Chosin Reservoir, North Korea, when his unit was attacked. Following the battle, his remains could not be recovered. Following the 2018 summit between President Donald Trump and Kim Jong-un, North Korea turned over 55 boxes, purported to contain the remains of American service members killed during the Korean War. The remains were sent to the Defense Pow/MIA Accounting Agency in Hawaii for identification.  The agency announced in September 2019 that Cpl. Avant had been identified.  Cpl. Avant‚Äôs remains arrived at the Jackson International Airport this morning and were escorted to Greenwood for a Friday service and burial at Odd Fellows Cemetery. He was escorted by local law enforcement officers and the Patriot Guard Riders on I-55.  Madison police and firefighters were in attendance on the I-55 bridge to honor the procession and Cpl. Avant‚Äôs service.
